<h2>HVAC Systems for Charleston</h2>
<p>Charleston's hot-humid climate demands HVAC systems specifically designed for coastal conditions. The ideal system should feature a SEER rating of at least 16-18 for optimal efficiency during the city's long cooling season, which typically runs from April through October. Heat pumps are particularly effective in Charleston's moderate winter climate, providing both heating and cooling while consuming less energy than traditional systems.</p>

<p>Due to Charleston's high humidity levels, proper dehumidification is crucial. Variable-speed air handlers and two-stage compressors help maintain consistent humidity control while reducing energy consumption. Salt air from the nearby Atlantic Ocean requires HVAC equipment with corrosion-resistant components and regular maintenance. Ductwork should be properly sealed and insulated to prevent moisture infiltration, which is common in Charleston's humid environment. For homes with solar panels, pairing a high-efficiency heat pump with smart thermostats can maximize the use of solar-generated electricity during peak production hours.</p>

<h2>Charleston Energy Incentives</h2>
<p>Charleston residents benefit from several attractive solar incentives that significantly reduce installation costs. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% credit on the total system cost through 2032, then steps down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to both solar panels and solar-powered HVAC systems, making comprehensive energy upgrades more affordable.</p>

<p>South Carolina offers additional incentives including a state tax credit of up to \$3,500 or 25% of system costs, whichever is less. The state also exempts solar installations from property taxes, ensuring your home's increased value won't result in higher tax bills. SCE&G participates in net metering, allowing customers to sell excess solar energy back to the grid at retail rates. The utility also offers rebates for high-efficiency HVAC equipment, with up to \$750 for qualifying heat pumps and air conditioners. Charleston County provides expedited permitting for solar installations, reducing installation time and costs.</p>

